Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{0.5%tsp}. Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Pour a large glug of @oil{some} into a #roasting tray{}. Pop it onto the top shelf of your oven to warm up. Pour a little @oil{some} into the bottom of another #baking tray{}. Snip the string holding the @whole British chicken{1/3} legs together, remove and discard. Pop the chicken on the tray and drizzle over a little @oil{some}. Season with @salt{some} and @pepper{some}. Roast on the middle shelf of your oven for ~{60-75%minutes} depending on size.

> The chicken is cooked when the juices from the thigh run clear.
> Remember to wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Meanwhile, peel the @potatoes{900} and chop into 4cm chunks. Add the potatoes to the @boiling water{215%ml} and cook for ~{7-8%minutes} or until the edges have softened when you poke them with a #knife{}. Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{}, pop back into the pan then sprinkle on half the @plain flour{12%g}. Give your pan a shake to fluff up the potato. Take your hot baking tray out of your oven, carefully transfer your potatoes onto it in a single layer, turning in the oil. Season with @salt{some}. Roast the potatoes on the top shelf of your oven for ~{45-50%minutes}, turning halfway. When they're ready, turn off the oven and place on the bottom shelf to keep warm until everything is ready.

Fill and boil your #kettle{}. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Quarter the @red cabbage{1}, remove (and discard) the white core, thinly slice. Coarsely grate the @pear{1}(coarsely grated, core discarded). Finely chop the @chestnut mushrooms{150%g}(finely chopped). Heat half the @unsalted butter{15%g} in a #frying pan{} on medium high heat - once melted, add the mushrooms. Fry until golden brown, ~{5-6%minutes}. While the mushrooms cook, pop the @Paxo stuffing{1} mixture into a #bowl{} and pour in the @boiling water{75%ml} (for the stuffing). Stir, then leave to stand for ~{5%minutes}. When the mushrooms are cooked, add the garlic, cook for ~{1%minute}. Then add them to the stuffing mixture and stir together. Transfer to a #small ovenproof dish{} and set aside.

Pop your frying pan back on medium-high heat (no need to wash). Add a drizzle of @oil{some} and the @chorizo{60%g} and onion. Stir and cook until the chorizo is crispy and the onion is really nice and soft, ~{4-6%minutes}. Stir in the @balsamic vinegar{12%ml} and cook for ~{1%minute}, then add the pear and red cabbage. Season with @salt{some} and @pepper{some}. Stir everything together, then pour in the @water{75%ml} (for the cabbage), bring to a simmer, cover with a #lid{} or some #foil{}, reduce the heat to medium low and cook until the cabbage is softened, ~{25-30%minutes}. Stir a couple of times to ensure it's not sticking to the pan.

Meanwhile, put a saucepan on medium-high heat and add the remaining @unsalted butter{15%g}. Melt the butter gently, then stir in the remaining @plain flour{12%g}. Continue to stir until combined, you've made a roux! Cook, stirring until the roux is a medium brown colour, ~{3-4%minutes}. Gradually stir in the @boiling water{215%ml} and @chicken stock paste{1}. Bring to the boil, stirring out any lumps that form. Lower the heat and simmer, stirring occasionally, until the gravy has thickened to your liking, ~{15-20%minutes}. Meanwhile, pop the stuffing in the oven to cook for ~{20%minutes}.

When the chicken is cooked, cover it loosely with #foil{} and leave to rest for ~{15-20%minutes}. Once the red cabbage is tender, remove the lid and simmer until the liquid has evaporated, ~{4-5%minutes}. Cover with a lid and set aside. A couple of minutes before everything is ready, heat through your gravy. Add any chicken resting juices or water to the gravy to get it to your desired consistency. Reheat your red cabbage too if you need to. Once everything is ready, carve the chicken. Share the veggies and spuds between your plates. Arrange the chicken alongside. Pour over the gravy and dig in!